item_id.text:
# Intensified Antitrust Scrutiny of Healthcare M&A

**Heightened Federal Enforcement:** U.S. antitrust enforcers have recently made healthcare mergers a top priority, reversing decades of relatively lax oversight ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2024/04/24/hospital-antitrust-enforcement#:~:text=Yes%2C%20but%3A%20The%20Biden%20administration,to%20challenge%20health%20care%20deals)) ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2024/04/24/hospital-antitrust-enforcement#:~:text=A%20recent%20study%20published%20in,Biden%20administration%20has%20focused%20on)). The Biden administration directed the FTC and DOJ to vigorously police hospital, insurance, and pharmaceutical deals, aiming to curb consolidation that drives up costs ([www.reedsmith.com](https://www.reedsmith.com/de/perspectives/managed-care-outlook-2024/2024/01/antitrust-developments-in-2024-that-will-impact-managed-care#:~:text=Efforts%20by%20private%20plaintiffs%20and,clearance%20statutes%20specifically%20governing%20even)). In 2023 the FTC ramped up enforcement, launching its **first-ever challenge to a private equity “roll-up” acquisition scheme** and blocking multiple healthcare mergers on traditional antitrust grounds ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=2023%20saw%20a%20significant%20uptick,head%20competition%20and%20harm%20customers)). These efforts reflect a **significant uptick** in scrutiny of healthcare M&A, with regulators more willing than before to litigate deals seen as anti-competitive ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=2023%20saw%20a%20significant%20uptick,head%20competition%20and%20harm%20customers)).

**Mixed Courtroom Results:** The stepped-up enforcement has met with both victories and setbacks. Regulators scored wins in late 2023 by derailing deals that combined direct competitors – for example, the FTC’s challenge forced John Muir Health to abandon its merger with San Ramon Regional Medical Center, which would have given the system over 50% of the local hospital market ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=FTC%20challenge%20causes%20parties%20to,insurers%2C%20leading%20to%20higher%20prices)). Likewise, the FTC successfully moved to block IQVIA’s acquisition of Propel Media in the health advertising space, with a judge agreeing it would harm competition ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=FTC%20success%20in%20challenge%20to,a%20prolonged%20Second%20Request%20investigation)) ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=The%20FTC%E2%80%99s%20win%20in%20IQVIA%2FPropel,judicial%20attention%20than%20market%20shares)). However, **not all challenges succeeded**. In mid-2024, a federal court denied the FTC’s bid to preliminarily halt Novant Health’s $320 million purchase of two North Carolina hospitals, finding the agency hadn’t met its burden and noting potential benefits of the deal ([www.reuters.com](https://www.reuters.com/legal/government/ftc-loses-bid-block-320-million-hospital-merger-north-carolina-2024-06-05/#:~:text=A%20U,June%2026%2C%20with%20both%20sides)). These mixed outcomes underscore that while agencies are more aggressive, courts still require strong evidence of harm and may credit efficiency claims.

**Targeting Private Equity “Roll-Ups”:** A notable development is the focus on private equity buyouts of physician practices and other providers. Antitrust officials suspect that serial acquisitions by PE firms – so-called **“roll-up” strategies** – can substantially lessen competition over time ([www.reedsmith.com](https://www.reedsmith.com/de/perspectives/managed-care-outlook-2024/2024/01/antitrust-developments-in-2024-that-will-impact-managed-care#:~:text=directly,and%20market%20allocation%20agreements%20with)) ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=2023%20saw%20a%20significant%20uptick,head%20competition%20and%20harm%20customers)). In a first-of-its-kind case, the FTC sued private-equity firm Welsh Carson and its portfolio company U.S. Anesthesia Partners in 2023, alleging they spent a decade consolidating anesthesiology practices in Texas to monopolize that market ([www.reedsmith.com](https://www.reedsmith.com/de/perspectives/managed-care-outlook-2024/2024/01/antitrust-developments-in-2024-that-will-impact-managed-care#:~:text=directly,and%20market%20allocation%20agreements%20with)). The agency claims this roll-up drove up prices and even involved unlawful price-setting agreements among remaining competitors ([www.reedsmith.com](https://www.reedsmith.com/de/perspectives/managed-care-outlook-2024/2024/01/antitrust-developments-in-2024-that-will-impact-managed-care#:~:text=Carson%2C%20that%20consolidated%20anesthesia%20practices,lawsuit%20exceeds%20its%20contractual%20and)). This bold approach faced headwinds: a judge in 2024 **dismissed the claims against the PE firm** (which was a minority investor), finding the FTC hadn’t shown the investor itself violated antitrust laws ([www.reuters.com](https://www.reuters.com/legal/government/pe-firm-welsh-carson-dodges-ftc-case-over-us-anesthesia-partners-acquisitions-2024-05-14/#:~:text=A%20U,The%20case)). The case against the provider entity continues, and the FTC’s push signaled to the industry that **aggregating many small healthcare providers can trigger antitrust scrutiny**. Even though the initial outcome was a setback for the FTC ([www.reuters.com](https://www.reuters.com/legal/government/pe-firm-welsh-carson-dodges-ftc-case-over-us-anesthesia-partners-acquisitions-2024-05-14/#:~:text=continue%20its%20antitrust%20case%20against,The%20case)), the inquiry itself – joined by the Department of Health and Human Services – highlights authorities’ concern that PE-driven consolidation may hurt patients through higher prices or lower quality ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/09/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-quarterly-update-q2-2024#:~:text=A.%20Cross,enrich%20executives%20but%20leave%20the)). We may see further attempts to unwind anti-competitive roll-ups as enforcers refine their legal tactics.

**New Merger Guidelines and Theories of Harm:** Federal agencies are also updating the playbook they use to evaluate healthcare deals. In late 2023, the FTC and DOJ proposed **new merger guidelines** (since approved) that lower the thresholds for challenging mergers and emphasize a broader range of harms ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2024/04/24/hospital-antitrust-enforcement#:~:text=Yes%2C%20but%3A%20The%20Biden%20administration,to%20challenge%20health%20care%20deals)). For healthcare transactions, this means regulators can more easily presume a hospital or clinic merger is illegal if it leads to high market shares or concentration ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=Here%20again%2C%20the%20FTC%20did,law%20by%20exploring%20nontraditional%20theories)). The new guidelines and recent enforcement rhetoric highlight **novel theories** beyond classic price effects. Regulators have signaled they will consider how mergers affect **labor markets** (e.g. whether a hospital merger lets the combined entity suppress wages for nurses or doctors) and **quality of care** for patients ([www.justice.gov](https://www.justice.gov/archives/opa/pr/justice-department-sues-block-unitedhealth-groups-acquisition-home-health-and-hospice#:~:text=commitment%20to%20ensuring%20that%20consolidation,%E2%80%9D)) ([www.justice.gov](https://www.justice.gov/archives/opa/pr/justice-department-sues-block-unitedhealth-groups-acquisition-home-health-and-hospice#:~:text=better%20and%20better%20quality%E2%80%9D%20to,UnitedHealth%E2%80%99s%20market%20share)). For instance, the DOJ’s 2024 lawsuit to block UnitedHealth Group’s $3.3 billion takeover of home health provider Amedisys argued the deal could reduce care quality for vulnerable patients and undermine competition for hiring home-health nurses ([www.justice.gov](https://www.justice.gov/archives/opa/pr/justice-department-sues-block-unitedhealth-groups-acquisition-home-health-and-hospice#:~:text=deserve%20affordable%2C%20high%20quality%20care,%E2%80%9D)) ([www.justice.gov](https://www.justice.gov/archives/opa/pr/justice-department-sues-block-unitedhealth-groups-acquisition-home-health-and-hospice#:~:text=better%20and%20better%20quality%E2%80%9D%20to,UnitedHealth%E2%80%99s%20market%20share)). Likewise, the FTC showed a willingness to prevent mergers that could harm future innovation or patient data privacy. In a notable case, it even challenged Amgen’s $27.8 billion acquisition of Horizon Therapeutics despite no overlapping products, using a “bundled products” theory (concern that Amgen might leverage its drug portfolio to thwart rivals to Horizon’s medicines) ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2023/05/16/ftc-amgen-horizon#:~:text=The%20Federal%20Trade%20Commission%20,the%20FTC%20has%20permitted%20pharmaceutical)). That pharmaceutical case was settled with Amgen agreeing not to bundle certain drugs, but it marked the **toughest stance on pharma M&A in over a decade** ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2023/05/16/ftc-amgen-horizon#:~:text=The%20Federal%20Trade%20Commission%20,divested%2C%20which%20it%20did%20for)). Overall, these developments demonstrate that antitrust enforcers are testing **expanded interpretations of harm** in healthcare mergers – including impacts on innovation, data, patient outcomes, and employees – rather than focusing solely on consumer prices.

**State-Level Oversight and Legislation:** Another major change is the surge in state involvement in healthcare antitrust. Over a dozen states have enacted their own **pre-merger review laws** that go beyond federal requirements, aiming to catch even smaller healthcare deals that might slip under the federal radar ([www.reedsmith.com](https://www.reedsmith.com/de/perspectives/managed-care-outlook-2024/2024/01/antitrust-developments-in-2024-that-will-impact-managed-care#:~:text=Similarly%2C%202023%20saw%20private%20antitrust,and%20hold%20implications%20for%20managed)). For example, **California** in 2024 began requiring healthcare entities to give 90 days’ notice of transactions to a new Office of Health Care Affordability, which can trigger a cost and market impact review ([www.mondaq.com](https://www.mondaq.com/unitedstates/antitrust-eu-competition/1576256/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect-later-in-2025#:~:text=California,have%20been%20required%20to)).  Similarly, states like **Massachusetts, New York, Washington, Oregon, and Connecticut** have adopted or proposed “mini-HSR” laws mandating state notification or approval for mergers, acquisitions, and even certain physician group sales ([www.mondaq.com](https://www.mondaq.com/unitedstates/antitrust-eu-competition/1576256/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect-later-in-2025#:~:text=At%20the%20state%20level%2C%20transaction,specific%20scrutiny%20of%20private)) ([www.mondaq.com](https://www.mondaq.com/unitedstates/antitrust-eu-competition/1576256/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect-later-in-2025#:~:text=Connecticut,since%20attempts%20to%20update%20existing)). # Intensified Antitrust Scrutiny of Healthcare M&A

**Heightened Federal Enforcement:** U.S. antitrust enforcers have recently made healthcare mergers a top priority, reversing decades of relatively lax oversight ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2024/04/24/hospital-antitrust-enforcement#:~:text=Yes%2C%20but%3A%20The%20Biden%20administration,to%20challenge%20health%20care%20deals)) ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2024/04/24/hospital-antitrust-enforcement#:~:text=A%20recent%20study%20published%20in,Biden%20administration%20has%20focused%20on)). The Biden administration directed the FTC and DOJ to vigorously police hospital, insurance, and pharmaceutical deals, aiming to curb consolidation that drives up costs ([www.reedsmith.com](https://www.reedsmith.com/de/perspectives/managed-care-outlook-2024/2024/01/antitrust-developments-in-2024-that-will-impact-managed-care#:~:text=Efforts%20by%20private%20plaintiffs%20and,clearance%20statutes%20specifically%20governing%20even)). In 2023 the FTC ramped up enforcement, launching its **first-ever challenge to a private equity “roll-up” acquisition scheme** and blocking multiple healthcare mergers on traditional antitrust grounds ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=2023%20saw%20a%20significant%20uptick,head%20competition%20and%20harm%20customers)). These efforts reflect a **significant uptick** in scrutiny of healthcare M&A, with regulators more willing than before to litigate deals seen as anti-competitive ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=2023%20saw%20a%20significant%20uptick,head%20competition%20and%20harm%20customers)).

**Mixed Courtroom Results:** The stepped-up enforcement has met with both victories and setbacks. Regulators scored wins in late 2023 by derailing deals that combined direct competitors – for example, the FTC’s challenge forced John Muir Health to abandon its merger with San Ramon Regional Medical Center, which would have given the system over 50% of the local hospital market ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=FTC%20challenge%20causes%20parties%20to,insurers%2C%20leading%20to%20higher%20prices)). Likewise, the FTC successfully moved to block IQVIA’s acquisition of Propel Media in the health advertising space, with a judge agreeing it would harm competition ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=FTC%20success%20in%20challenge%20to,a%20prolonged%20Second%20Request%20investigation)) ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=The%20FTC%E2%80%99s%20win%20in%20IQVIA%2FPropel,judicial%20attention%20than%20market%20shares)). However, **not all challenges succeeded**. In mid-2024, a federal court denied the FTC’s bid to preliminarily halt Novant Health’s $320 million purchase of two North Carolina hospitals, finding the agency hadn’t met its burden and noting potential benefits of the deal ([www.reuters.com](https://www.reuters.com/legal/government/ftc-loses-bid-block-320-million-hospital-merger-north-carolina-2024-06-05/#:~:text=A%20U,June%2026%2C%20with%20both%20sides)). These mixed outcomes underscore that while agencies are more aggressive, courts still require strong evidence of harm and may credit efficiency claims.

**Targeting Private Equity “Roll-Ups”:** A notable development is the focus on private equity buyouts of physician practices and other providers. Antitrust officials suspect that serial acquisitions by PE firms – so-called **“roll-up” strategies** – can substantially lessen competition over time ([www.reedsmith.com](https://www.reedsmith.com/de/perspectives/managed-care-outlook-2024/2024/01/antitrust-developments-in-2024-that-will-impact-managed-care#:~:text=directly,and%20market%20allocation%20agreements%20with)) ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=2023%20saw%20a%20significant%20uptick,head%20competition%20and%20harm%20customers)). In a first-of-its-kind case, the FTC sued private-equity firm Welsh Carson and its portfolio company U.S. Anesthesia Partners in 2023, alleging they spent a decade consolidating anesthesiology practices in Texas to monopolize that market ([www.reedsmith.com](https://www.reedsmith.com/de/perspectives/managed-care-outlook-2024/2024/01/antitrust-developments-in-2024-that-will-impact-managed-care#:~:text=directly,and%20market%20allocation%20agreements%20with)). # Intensified Antitrust Scrutiny of Healthcare M&A

**Heightened Federal Enforcement:** U.S. antitrust enforcers have recently made healthcare mergers a top priority, reversing decades of relatively lax oversight ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2024/04/24/hospital-antitrust-enforcement#:~:text=Yes%2C%20but%3A%20The%20Biden%20administration,to%20challenge%20health%20care%20deals)) ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2024/04/24/hospital-antitrust-enforcement#:~:text=A%20recent%20study%20published%20in,Biden%20administration%20has%20focused%20on)). The Biden administration directed the FTC and DOJ to vigorously police hospital, insurance, and pharmaceutical deals, aiming to curb consolidation that drives up costs ([www.reedsmith.com](https://www.reedsmith.com/de/perspectives/managed-care-outlook-2024/2024/01/antitrust-developments-in-2024-that-will-impact-managed-care#:~:text=Efforts%20by%20private%20plaintiffs%20and,clearance%20statutes%20specifically%20governing%20even)). In 2023 the FTC ramped up enforcement, launching its **first-ever challenge to a private equity “roll-up” acquisition scheme** and blocking multiple healthcare mergers on traditional antitrust grounds ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=2023%20saw%20a%20significant%20uptick,head%20competition%20and%20harm%20customers)). These efforts reflect a **significant uptick** in scrutiny of healthcare M&A, with regulators more willing than before to litigate deals seen as anti-competitive ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=2023%20saw%20a%20significant%20uptick,head%20competition%20and%20harm%20customers)).

**Mixed Courtroom Results:** The stepped-up enforcement has met with both victories and setbacks. Regulators scored wins in late 2023 by derailing deals that combined direct competitors – for example, the FTC’s challenge forced John Muir Health to abandon its merger with San Ramon Regional Medical Center, which would have given the system over 50% of the local hospital market ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=FTC%20challenge%20causes%20parties%20to,insurers%2C%20leading%20to%20higher%20prices)). Likewise, the FTC successfully moved to block IQVIA’s acquisition of Propel Media in the health advertising space, with a judge agreeing it would harm competition ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=FTC%20success%20in%20challenge%20to,a%20prolonged%20Second%20Request%20investigation)) ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=The%20FTC%E2%80%99s%20win%20in%20IQVIA%2FPropel,judicial%20attention%20than%20market%20shares)). However, **not all challenges succeeded**. In mid-2024, a federal court denied the FTC’s bid to preliminarily halt Novant Health’s $320 million purchase of two North Carolina hospitals, finding the agency hadn’t met its burden and noting potential benefits of the deal ([www.reuters.com](https://www.reuters.com/legal/government/ftc-loses-bid-block-320-million-hospital-merger-north-carolina-2024-06-05/#:~:text=A%20U,June%2026%2C%20with%20both%20sides)). These mixed outcomes underscore that while agencies are more aggressive, courts still require strong evidence of harm and may credit efficiency claims.

**Targeting Private Equity “Roll-Ups”:** A notable development is the focus on private equity buyouts of physician practices and other providers. Antitrust officials suspect that serial acquisitions by PE firms – so-called **“roll-up” strategies** – can substantially lessen competition over time ([www.reedsmith.com](https://www.reedsmith.com/de/perspectives/managed-care-outlook-2024/2024/01/antitrust-developments-in-2024-that-will-impact-managed-care#:~:text=directly,and%20market%20allocation%20agreements%20with)) ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=2023%20saw%20a%20significant%20uptick,head%20competition%20and%20harm%20customers)). In a first-of-its-kind case, the FTC sued private-equity firm Welsh Carson and its portfolio company U.S. Anesthesia Partners in 2023, alleging they spent a decade consolidating anesthesiology practices in Texas to monopolize that market ([www.reedsmith.com](https://www.reedsmith.com/de/perspectives/managed-care-outlook-2024/2024/01/antitrust-developments-in-2024-that-will-impact-managed-care#:~:text=directly,and%20market%20allocation%20agreements%20with)). The agency claims this roll-up drove up prices and even involved unlawful price-setting agreements among remaining competitors ([www.reedsmith.com](https://www.reedsmith.com/de/perspectives/managed-care-outlook-2024/2024/01/antitrust-developments-in-2024-that-will-impact-managed-care#:~:text=Carson%2C%20that%20consolidated%20anesthesia%20practices,lawsuit%20exceeds%20its%20contractual%20and)). This bold approach faced headwinds: a judge in 2024 **dismissed the claims against the PE firm** (which was a minority investor), finding the FTC hadn’t shown the investor itself violated antitrust laws ([www.reuters.com](https://www.reuters.com/legal/government/pe-firm-welsh-carson-dodges-ftc-case-over-us-anesthesia-partners-acquisitions-2024-05-14/#:~:text=A%20U,The%20case)). The case against the provider entity continues, and the FTC’s push signaled to the industry that **aggregating many small healthcare providers can trigger antitrust scrutiny**. Even though the initial outcome was a setback for the FTC ([www.reuters.com](https://www.reuters.com/legal/government/pe-firm-welsh-carson-dodges-ftc-case-over-us-anesthesia-partners-acquisitions-2024-05-14/#:~:text=continue%20its%20antitrust%20case%20against,The%20case)), the inquiry itself – joined by the Department of Health and Human Services – highlights authorities’ concern that PE-driven consolidation may hurt patients through higher prices or lower quality ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/09/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-quarterly-update-q2-2024#:~:text=A.%20Cross,enrich%20executives%20but%20leave%20the)). We may see further attempts to unwind anti-competitive roll-ups as enforcers refine their legal tactics.

**New Merger Guidelines and Theories of Harm:** Federal agencies are also updating the playbook they use to evaluate healthcare deals. In late 2023, the FTC and DOJ proposed **new merger guidelines** (since approved) that lower the thresholds for challenging mergers and emphasize a broader range of harms ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2024/04/24/hospital-antitrust-enforcement#:~:text=Yes%2C%20but%3A%20The%20Biden%20administration,to%20challenge%20health%20care%20deals)). For healthcare transactions, this means regulators can more easily presume a hospital or clinic merger is illegal if it leads to high market shares or concentration ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=Here%20again%2C%20the%20FTC%20did,law%20by%20exploring%20nontraditional%20theories)). The new guidelines and recent enforcement rhetoric highlight **novel theories** beyond classic price effects. Regulators have signaled they will consider how mergers affect **labor markets** (e.g. whether a hospital merger lets the combined entity suppress wages for nurses or doctors) and **quality of care** for patients ([www.justice.gov](https://www.justice.gov/archives/opa/pr/justice-department-sues-block-unitedhealth-groups-acquisition-home-health-and-hospice#:~:text=commitment%20to%20ensuring%20that%20consolidation,%E2%80%9D)) ([www.justice.gov](https://www.justice.gov/archives/opa/pr/justice-department-sues-block-unitedhealth-groups-acquisition-home-health-and-hospice#:~:text=better%20and%20better%20quality%E2%80%9D%20to,UnitedHealth%E2%80%99s%20market%20share)). For instance, the DOJ’s 2024 lawsuit to block UnitedHealth Group’s $3.3 billion takeover of home health provider Amedisys argued the deal could reduce care quality for vulnerable patients and undermine competition for hiring home-health nurses ([www.justice.gov](https://www.justice.gov/archives/opa/pr/justice-department-sues-block-unitedhealth-groups-acquisition-home-health-and-hospice#:~:text=deserve%20affordable%2C%20high%20quality%20care,%E2%80%9D)) ([www.justice.gov](https://www.justice.gov/archives/opa/pr/justice-department-sues-block-unitedhealth-groups-acquisition-home-health-and-hospice#:~:text=better%20and%20better%20quality%E2%80%9D%20to,UnitedHealth%E2%80%99s%20market%20share)). Likewise, the FTC showed a willingness to prevent mergers that could harm future innovation or patient data privacy. In a notable case, it even challenged Amgen’s $27.8 billion acquisition of Horizon Therapeutics despite no overlapping products, using a “bundled products” theory (concern that Amgen might leverage its drug portfolio to thwart rivals to Horizon’s medicines) ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2023/05/16/ftc-amgen-horizon#:~:text=The%20Federal%20Trade%20Commission%20,the%20FTC%20has%20permitted%20pharmaceutical)). That pharmaceutical case was settled with Amgen agreeing not to bundle certain drugs, but it marked the **toughest stance on pharma M&A in over a decade** ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2023/05/16/ftc-amgen-horizon#:~:text=The%20Federal%20Trade%20Commission%20,divested%2C%20which%20it%20did%20for)). Overall, these developments demonstrate that antitrust enforcers are testing **expanded interpretations of harm** in healthcare mergers – including impacts on innovation, data, patient outcomes, and employees – rather than focusing solely on consumer prices.

**State-Level Oversight and Legislation:** Another major change is the surge in state involvement in healthcare antitrust. Over a dozen states have enacted their own **pre-merger review laws** that go beyond federal requirements, aiming to catch even smaller healthcare deals that might slip under the federal radar ([www.reedsmith.com](https://www.reedsmith.com/de/perspectives/managed-care-outlook-2024/2024/01/antitrust-developments-in-2024-that-will-impact-managed-care#:~:text=Similarly%2C%202023%20saw%20private%20antitrust,and%20hold%20implications%20for%20managed)). For example, **California** in 2024 began requiring healthcare entities to give 90 days’ notice of transactions to a new Office of Health Care Affordability, which can trigger a cost and market impact review ([www.mondaq.com](https://www.mondaq.com/unitedstates/antitrust-eu-competition/1576256/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect-later-in-2025#:~:text=California,have%20been%20required%20to)).  Similarly, states like **Massachusetts, New York, Washington, Oregon, and Connecticut** have adopted or proposed “mini-HSR” laws mandating state notification or approval for mergers, acquisitions, and even certain physician group sales ([www.mondaq.com](https://www.mondaq.com/unitedstates/antitrust-eu-competition/1576256/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect-later-in-2025#:~:text=At%20the%20state%20level%2C%20transaction,specific%20scrutiny%20of%20private)) ([www.mondaq.com](https://www.mondaq.com/unitedstates/antitrust-eu-competition/1576256/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect-later-in-2025#:~:text=Connecticut,since%20attempts%20to%20update%20existing)). These laws seek to address local consolidation trends – for instance, some target hospital mergers that might raise prices in rural areas, while others specifically scrutinize private equity purchases of hospitals or physician practices ([www.mondaq.com](https://www.mondaq.com/unitedstates/antitrust-eu-competition/1576256/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect-later-in-2025#:~:text=regulatory%20activity%2C%20with%20states%20taking,1)) ([www.mondaq.com](https://www.mondaq.com/unitedstates/antitrust-eu-competition/1576256/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect-later-in-2025#:~:text=Connecticut,review%20healthcare%20transactions%20and%20an)). The goal is to protect patients from higher costs and reduced access by giving states a say in deals that historically only faced federal review. At the same time, certain states have **encouraged consolidation** via Certificate of Public Advantage (COPA) laws or legislative exemptions. In 2023, North Carolina legislators even considered exempting large state-affiliated health systems from antitrust laws, a move the FTC publicly opposed for potentially shielding anti-competitive hospital monopolies ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2023/06/08/ftc-opposes-north-carolinas-antitrust-hospital-legislation#:~:text=2023,it%20may%20encourage%20health%20care)). This patchwork of state actions means healthcare M&A now faces heightened scrutiny on multiple fronts. Transactions may need sign-off from state health agencies or attorneys general in addition to clearing federal antitrust review, adding new hurdles and complexity for healthcare companies.

**Key Takeaways:** Today’s antitrust landscape for healthcare M&A is far more stringent than in the past. Regulators are no longer acquiescing to consolidation; instead, they are actively litigating to block mergers that threaten competition, even if the deals are smaller or involve novel theories of harm ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=2023%20saw%20a%20significant%20uptick,head%20competition%20and%20harm%20customers)) ([www.reuters.com](https://www.reuters.com/legal/government/ftc-loses-bid-block-320-million-hospital-merger-north-carolina-2024-06-05/#:~:text=A%20U,June%2026%2C%20with%20both%20sides)). Federal authorities, emboldened by new guidelines and a pro-enforcement agenda, are challenging mergers of hospitals, insurers, and drugmakers that they believe will lead to higher prices, lower quality, or stifle innovation ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2024/04/24/hospital-antitrust-enforcement#:~:text=Yes%2C%20but%3A%20The%20Biden%20administration,to%20challenge%20health%20care%20deals)) ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2023/05/16/ftc-amgen-horizon#:~:text=The%20Federal%20Trade%20Commission%20,the%20FTC%20has%20permitted%20pharmaceutical)). While some of these aggressive efforts have been checked by courts, they have already deterred or unwound a number of deals and put the healthcare industry on notice. In parallel, state governments are increasingly stepping in with their own oversight regimes to monitor and regulate healthcare consolidation ([www.reedsmith.com](https://www.reedsmith.com/de/perspectives/managed-care-outlook-2024/2024/01/antitrust-developments-in-2024-that-will-impact-managed-care#:~:text=Similarly%2C%202023%20saw%20private%20antitrust,and%20hold%20implications%20for%20managed)) ([www.mondaq.com](https://www.mondaq.com/unitedstates/antitrust-eu-competition/1576256/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect-later-in-2025#:~:text=California,have%20been%20required%20to)). In short, the **latest developments** in antitrust law show a clear trend toward tougher scrutiny of healthcare mergers and acquisitions. Merging parties in healthcare must now anticipate close examinations of how their deal will affect competition – not just in terms of prices for patients, but across the entire ecosystem, including quality of care, labor conditions, and innovation. This robust enforcement environment may slow the pace of mega-mergers and force companies to design mergers (or remedies) that can withstand the new antitrust gauntlet, ultimately aiming to protect consumers and patients from the downsides of excessive consolidation ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2024/04/24/hospital-antitrust-enforcement#:~:text=regulators%20significantly%20under,Biden%20administration%20has%20focused%20on)) ([www.justice.gov](https://www.justice.gov/archives/opa/pr/justice-department-sues-block-unitedhealth-groups-acquisition-home-health-and-hospice#:~:text=deserve%20affordable%2C%20high%20quality%20care,%E2%80%9D)).

content.text:
# Intensified Antitrust Scrutiny of Healthcare M&A

**Heightened Federal Enforcement:** U.S. antitrust enforcers have recently made healthcare mergers a top priority, reversing decades of relatively lax oversight ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2024/04/24/hospital-antitrust-enforcement#:~:text=Yes%2C%20but%3A%20The%20Biden%20administration,to%20challenge%20health%20care%20deals)) ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2024/04/24/hospital-antitrust-enforcement#:~:text=A%20recent%20study%20published%20in,Biden%20administration%20has%20focused%20on)). The Biden administration directed the FTC and DOJ to vigorously police hospital, insurance, and pharmaceutical deals, aiming to curb consolidation that drives up costs ([www.reedsmith.com](https://www.reedsmith.com/de/perspectives/managed-care-outlook-2024/2024/01/antitrust-developments-in-2024-that-will-impact-managed-care#:~:text=Efforts%20by%20private%20plaintiffs%20and,clearance%20statutes%20specifically%20governing%20even)). In 2023 the FTC ramped up enforcement, launching its **first-ever challenge to a private equity “roll-up” acquisition scheme** and blocking multiple healthcare mergers on traditional antitrust grounds ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=2023%20saw%20a%20significant%20uptick,head%20competition%20and%20harm%20customers)). These efforts reflect a **significant uptick** in scrutiny of healthcare M&A, with regulators more willing than before to litigate deals seen as anti-competitive ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=2023%20saw%20a%20significant%20uptick,head%20competition%20and%20harm%20customers)).

**Mixed Courtroom Results:** The stepped-up enforcement has met with both victories and setbacks. Regulators scored wins in late 2023 by derailing deals that combined direct competitors – for example, the FTC’s challenge forced John Muir Health to abandon its merger with San Ramon Regional Medical Center, which would have given the system over 50% of the local hospital market ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=FTC%20challenge%20causes%20parties%20to,insurers%2C%20leading%20to%20higher%20prices)). Likewise, the FTC successfully moved to block IQVIA’s acquisition of Propel Media in the health advertising space, with a judge agreeing it would harm competition ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=FTC%20success%20in%20challenge%20to,a%20prolonged%20Second%20Request%20investigation)) ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=The%20FTC%E2%80%99s%20win%20in%20IQVIA%2FPropel,judicial%20attention%20than%20market%20shares)). However, **not all challenges succeeded**. In mid-2024, a federal court denied the FTC’s bid to preliminarily halt Novant Health’s $320 million purchase of two North Carolina hospitals, finding the agency hadn’t met its burden and noting potential benefits of the deal ([www.reuters.com](https://www.reuters.com/legal/government/ftc-loses-bid-block-320-million-hospital-merger-north-carolina-2024-06-05/#:~:text=A%20U,June%2026%2C%20with%20both%20sides)). These mixed outcomes underscore that while agencies are more aggressive, courts still require strong evidence of harm and may credit efficiency claims.

**Targeting Private Equity “Roll-Ups”:** A notable development is the focus on private equity buyouts of physician practices and other providers. Antitrust officials suspect that serial acquisitions by PE firms – so-called **“roll-up” strategies** – can substantially lessen competition over time ([www.reedsmith.com](https://www.reedsmith.com/de/perspectives/managed-care-outlook-2024/2024/01/antitrust-developments-in-2024-that-will-impact-managed-care#:~:text=directly,and%20market%20allocation%20agreements%20with)) ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=2023%20saw%20a%20significant%20uptick,head%20competition%20and%20harm%20customers)). In a first-of-its-kind case, the FTC sued private-equity firm Welsh Carson and its portfolio company U.S. Anesthesia Partners in 2023, alleging they spent a decade consolidating anesthesiology practices in Texas to monopolize that market ([www.reedsmith.com](https://www.reedsmith.com/de/perspectives/managed-care-outlook-2024/2024/01/antitrust-developments-in-2024-that-will-impact-managed-care#:~:text=directly,and%20market%20allocation%20agreements%20with)). The agency claims this roll-up drove up prices and even involved unlawful price-setting agreements among remaining competitors ([www.reedsmith.com](https://www.reedsmith.com/de/perspectives/managed-care-outlook-2024/2024/01/antitrust-developments-in-2024-that-will-impact-managed-care#:~:text=Carson%2C%20that%20consolidated%20anesthesia%20practices,lawsuit%20exceeds%20its%20contractual%20and)). This bold approach faced headwinds: a judge in 2024 **dismissed the claims against the PE firm** (which was a minority investor), finding the FTC hadn’t shown the investor itself violated antitrust laws ([www.reuters.com](https://www.reuters.com/legal/government/pe-firm-welsh-carson-dodges-ftc-case-over-us-anesthesia-partners-acquisitions-2024-05-14/#:~:text=A%20U,The%20case)). The case against the provider entity continues, and the FTC’s push signaled to the industry that **aggregating many small healthcare providers can trigger antitrust scrutiny**. Even though the initial outcome was a setback for the FTC ([www.reuters.com](https://www.reuters.com/legal/government/pe-firm-welsh-carson-dodges-ftc-case-over-us-anesthesia-partners-acquisitions-2024-05-14/#:~:text=continue%20its%20antitrust%20case%20against,The%20case)), the inquiry itself – joined by the Department of Health and Human Services – highlights authorities’ concern that PE-driven consolidation may hurt patients through higher prices or lower quality ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/09/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-quarterly-update-q2-2024#:~:text=A.%20Cross,enrich%20executives%20but%20leave%20the)). We may see further attempts to unwind anti-competitive roll-ups as enforcers refine their legal tactics.

**New Merger Guidelines and Theories of Harm:** Federal agencies are also updating the playbook they use to evaluate healthcare deals. In late 2023, the FTC and DOJ proposed **new merger guidelines** (since approved) that lower the thresholds for challenging mergers and emphasize a broader range of harms ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2024/04/24/hospital-antitrust-enforcement#:~:text=Yes%2C%20but%3A%20The%20Biden%20administration,to%20challenge%20health%20care%20deals)). For healthcare transactions, this means regulators can more easily presume a hospital or clinic merger is illegal if it leads to high market shares or concentration ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=Here%20again%2C%20the%20FTC%20did,law%20by%20exploring%20nontraditional%20theories)). The new guidelines and recent enforcement rhetoric highlight **novel theories** beyond classic price effects. Regulators have signaled they will consider how mergers affect **labor markets** (e.g. whether a hospital merger lets the combined entity suppress wages for nurses or doctors) and **quality of care** for patients ([www.justice.gov](https://www.justice.gov/archives/opa/pr/justice-department-sues-block-unitedhealth-groups-acquisition-home-health-and-hospice#:~:text=commitment%20to%20ensuring%20that%20consolidation,%E2%80%9D)) ([www.justice.gov](https://www.justice.gov/archives/opa/pr/justice-department-sues-block-unitedhealth-groups-acquisition-home-health-and-hospice#:~:text=better%20and%20better%20quality%E2%80%9D%20to,UnitedHealth%E2%80%99s%20market%20share)). For instance, the DOJ’s 2024 lawsuit to block UnitedHealth Group’s $3.3 billion takeover of home health provider Amedisys argued the deal could reduce care quality for vulnerable patients and undermine competition for hiring home-health nurses ([www.justice.gov](https://www.justice.gov/archives/opa/pr/justice-department-sues-block-unitedhealth-groups-acquisition-home-health-and-hospice#:~:text=deserve%20affordable%2C%20high%20quality%20care,%E2%80%9D)) ([www.justice.gov](https://www.justice.gov/archives/opa/pr/justice-department-sues-block-unitedhealth-groups-acquisition-home-health-and-hospice#:~:text=better%20and%20better%20quality%E2%80%9D%20to,UnitedHealth%E2%80%99s%20market%20share)). Likewise, the FTC showed a willingness to prevent mergers that could harm future innovation or patient data privacy. In a notable case, it even challenged Amgen’s $27.8 billion acquisition of Horizon Therapeutics despite no overlapping products, using a “bundled products” theory (concern that Amgen might leverage its drug portfolio to thwart rivals to Horizon’s medicines) ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2023/05/16/ftc-amgen-horizon#:~:text=The%20Federal%20Trade%20Commission%20,the%20FTC%20has%20permitted%20pharmaceutical)). That pharmaceutical case was settled with Amgen agreeing not to bundle certain drugs, but it marked the **toughest stance on pharma M&A in over a decade** ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2023/05/16/ftc-amgen-horizon#:~:text=The%20Federal%20Trade%20Commission%20,divested%2C%20which%20it%20did%20for)). Overall, these developments demonstrate that antitrust enforcers are testing **expanded interpretations of harm** in healthcare mergers – including impacts on innovation, data, patient outcomes, and employees – rather than focusing solely on consumer prices.

**State-Level Oversight and Legislation:** Another major change is the surge in state involvement in healthcare antitrust. Over a dozen states have enacted their own **pre-merger review laws** that go beyond federal requirements, aiming to catch even smaller healthcare deals that might slip under the federal radar ([www.reedsmith.com](https://www.reedsmith.com/de/perspectives/managed-care-outlook-2024/2024/01/antitrust-developments-in-2024-that-will-impact-managed-care#:~:text=Similarly%2C%202023%20saw%20private%20antitrust,and%20hold%20implications%20for%20managed)). For example, **California** in 2024 began requiring healthcare entities to give 90 days’ notice of transactions to a new Office of Health Care Affordability, which can trigger a cost and market impact review ([www.mondaq.com](https://www.mondaq.com/unitedstates/antitrust-eu-competition/1576256/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect-later-in-2025#:~:text=California,have%20been%20required%20to)).  Similarly, states like **Massachusetts, New York, Washington, Oregon, and Connecticut** have adopted or proposed “mini-HSR” laws mandating state notification or approval for mergers, acquisitions, and even certain physician group sales ([www.mondaq.com](https://www.mondaq.com/unitedstates/antitrust-eu-competition/1576256/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect-later-in-2025#:~:text=At%20the%20state%20level%2C%20transaction,specific%20scrutiny%20of%20private)) ([www.mondaq.com](https://www.mondaq.com/unitedstates/antitrust-eu-competition/1576256/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect-later-in-2025#:~:text=Connecticut,since%20attempts%20to%20update%20existing)). These laws seek to address local consolidation trends – for instance, some target hospital mergers that might raise prices in rural areas, while others specifically scrutinize private equity purchases of hospitals or physician practices ([www.mondaq.com](https://www.mondaq.com/unitedstates/antitrust-eu-competition/1576256/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect-later-in-2025#:~:text=regulatory%20activity%2C%20with%20states%20taking,1)) ([www.mondaq.com](https://www.mondaq.com/unitedstates/antitrust-eu-competition/1576256/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect-later-in-2025#:~:text=Connecticut,review%20healthcare%20transactions%20and%20an)). The goal is to protect patients from higher costs and reduced access by giving states a say in deals that historically only faced federal review. At the same time, certain states have **encouraged consolidation** via Certificate of Public Advantage (COPA) laws or legislative exemptions. In 2023, North Carolina legislators even considered exempting large state-affiliated health systems from antitrust laws, a move the FTC publicly opposed for potentially shielding anti-competitive hospital monopolies ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2023/06/08/ftc-opposes-north-carolinas-antitrust-hospital-legislation#:~:text=2023,it%20may%20encourage%20health%20care)). This patchwork of state actions means healthcare M&A now faces heightened scrutiny on multiple fronts. Transactions may need sign-off from state health agencies or attorneys general in addition to clearing federal antitrust review, adding new hurdles and complexity for healthcare companies.

**Key Takeaways:** Today’s antitrust landscape for healthcare M&A is far more stringent than in the past. Regulators are no longer acquiescing to consolidation; instead, they are actively litigating to block mergers that threaten competition, even if the deals are smaller or involve novel theories of harm ([www.goodwinlaw.com](https://www.goodwinlaw.com/en/insights/publications/2024/03/insights-otherindustries-hltc-antitrust-competition-year-in-review-2023#:~:text=2023%20saw%20a%20significant%20uptick,head%20competition%20and%20harm%20customers)) ([www.reuters.com](https://www.reuters.com/legal/government/ftc-loses-bid-block-320-million-hospital-merger-north-carolina-2024-06-05/#:~:text=A%20U,June%2026%2C%20with%20both%20sides)). Federal authorities, emboldened by new guidelines and a pro-enforcement agenda, are challenging mergers of hospitals, insurers, and drugmakers that they believe will lead to higher prices, lower quality, or stifle innovation ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2024/04/24/hospital-antitrust-enforcement#:~:text=Yes%2C%20but%3A%20The%20Biden%20administration,to%20challenge%20health%20care%20deals)) ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2023/05/16/ftc-amgen-horizon#:~:text=The%20Federal%20Trade%20Commission%20,the%20FTC%20has%20permitted%20pharmaceutical)). While some of these aggressive efforts have been checked by courts, they have already deterred or unwound a number of deals and put the healthcare industry on notice. In parallel, state governments are increasingly stepping in with their own oversight regimes to monitor and regulate healthcare consolidation ([www.reedsmith.com](https://www.reedsmith.com/de/perspectives/managed-care-outlook-2024/2024/01/antitrust-developments-in-2024-that-will-impact-managed-care#:~:text=Similarly%2C%202023%20saw%20private%20antitrust,and%20hold%20implications%20for%20managed)) ([www.mondaq.com](https://www.mondaq.com/unitedstates/antitrust-eu-competition/1576256/a-year-end-report-for-healthcare-antitrust-and-what-to-expect-later-in-2025#:~:text=California,have%20been%20required%20to)). In short, the **latest developments** in antitrust law show a clear trend toward tougher scrutiny of healthcare mergers and acquisitions. Merging parties in healthcare must now anticipate close examinations of how their deal will affect competition – not just in terms of prices for patients, but across the entire ecosystem, including quality of care, labor conditions, and innovation. This robust enforcement environment may slow the pace of mega-mergers and force companies to design mergers (or remedies) that can withstand the new antitrust gauntlet, ultimately aiming to protect consumers and patients from the downsides of excessive consolidation ([www.axios.com](https://www.axios.com/2024/04/24/hospital-antitrust-enforcement#:~:text=regulators%20significantly%20under,Biden%20administration%20has%20focused%20on)) ([www.justice.gov](https://www.justice.gov/archives/opa/pr/justice-department-sues-block-unitedhealth-groups-acquisition-home-health-and-hospice#:~:text=deserve%20affordable%2C%20high%20quality%20care,%E2%80%9D)).
